therefore he became enamoured of her in her old age, she could not have been an old woman when he gave her this name. The boy in Ep. v. 98 is made to curse her and her fellows, and to predict that they will be stoned for a set of wicked old women, and Priapus describes her with false teeth (S. i. 8. 48); but these need not be taken literally. In Ep. xvii. 47, Horace says she is not an old woman 3 and there is no reason to suppose she was, though most probably she was not young. It is impossible, from Horace’s poems¹ to gather the cause of his anger against this woman or his connexion with her. If Gratidia was her real name, the fictitious one was framed on the principle noticed C. ii. 12, Introduction.
